i If one uses a parametric representation then the analytical description of IR-subgraphs in terms of the com-
pleteness condition is insufficient. This is because the structure of integrands in parametric representations is
characterized in a roundabout way via derivative graph-theoretic notions.


F.V.Tkachov, Phys. Part. Nucl. 25 (1994) 649  corrected 23.11.98 22




tion domain. This is done in two logical steps.
First, one notices that -- similarly to the case of the R-operation in coordinate representation -- the
expansion 4.7 (together with the counterterms already added) is integrable with a wider set of test func-
tions, not necessarily vanishing in an entire neighborhood of the origin. A proposition essentially
equivalent to the Bogoliubov-Parasiuk theorem is that such less restrictive test functions should only
have zero of second order (for a detailed discussion of the Bogoliubov-Parasiuk theorem in coordinate
representation from the distribution-theoretic point of view see [61; 101]). It is natural to assume that
the approximation properties of the expansion 4.7 are also preserved on such test functions. This is the
crucial analytical step in the proof.
Assuming that this has been proved, the second step is then straightforward and consists in con-
structing the counterterm for the singularity at p = p =
1 2 0 in exactly the same way as in the case of the
single propagator. Namely, the counterterm should be a linear combination of the -function and its
first-order derivatives while the coefficients have the form similar to 3.6. For instance, for the coeffi-
cient of the -function without derivatives one has:

